    "narrative": "The lineup for April 11th is anchored by **Corbin Carroll**, who stands as our clear top play with a commanding 87.14 efficiency score. Facing Walker, **Corbin Carroll** benefits from a strong park factor and a favorable matchup against a pitcher with a 4.79 xERA, with his ability to exploit the catcher's 1.86s pop time serving as the primary driver for a potential multi-SB game. Joining him in the elite tier is **Vinnie Pasquantino** (76.21) and **Mickey Moniak** (75.75). Both players are capitalizing on prime lineup positioning\u2014hitting 3rd\u2014and favorable matchups against Fedde and M\u00e1rquez, respectively. **Mickey Moniak** in particular benefits from the slow delivery of M\u00e1rquez, boosting his stolen base probability in a high-leverage spot.\n\nThe most difficult decision for the staff was the exclusion of **Trevor Story**, who sat just outside the active roster at 49.25. While his base projection was respectable, the optimizer favored the higher platoon-adjusted output of **Max Muncy** (51.08) and **Kyle Karros** (50.14). Although **Kyle Karros** occupies the undesirable 9-hole, the massive SP skill edge against the 5.26 xERA of M\u00e1rquez outweighed the stability offered by **Trevor Story** against a tougher arm like Kyle Leahy. We are monitoring **Dalton Rushing** and **Alex Freeland** closely, as both carry \"Lineup Pending\" designations and rely on favorable winds; if they are dropped into the bottom of the order or the wind shifts, we may see their efficiency scores dip below the 50-point threshold.\n\nGiven our organizational focus on the scarcity of SB, we continue to prioritize players like **Jazz Chisholm Jr.** (68.15) despite the park hit in his matchup against Nick Martinez. While **Jose Caballero** and **Zach McKinstry** were considered for their wheels, their negative platoon splits against today\u2019s right-handed starters made them inefficient options compared to the high-ceiling production of **Tyler Soderstrom** (68.67) and **James Wood** (62.67). We remain cautious regarding **Giancarlo Stanton**; his 60.79 score is adequate, but his limited stolen base upside makes him the most vulnerable candidate to be benched if we need to cycle in more speed-heavy assets from our reserves like **Brice Turang** or **Carson Williams** later this weekend.",
